<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the Mineral Products Association</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Mineral Products Association</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:12.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">The MPA is enthusiastic about offsetting, seeing potential benefits for the industry if it is implemented to deliver the benefits intended.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:12.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Our track record in delivering biodiversity gain and the potential to do more demonstrates the key role that the sector could play in being a major offset provider, through provision of habitats on its estate and restored sites.  This will require sufficient flexibility to be provided in any offsetting to enable the additionality requirements of offsetting to be met.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:12.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">We believe that minerals development should be acknowledged as different to other types of development given the scale of sites, the essentially temporary nature of development, and the ability to deliver enormous biodiversity gains through site restoration and aftercare.  Offsetting should be focused on ensuring other types of development (than minerals) in which there is limited ability to achieve no net loss and biodiversity gains.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:12.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Evidence to date, with few habitat compensation or offset schemes being delivered, suggests that either that the mitigation hierarchy is working, or that there needs to be a stronger requirement for residual impacts to be compensated for, including through offsetting.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:12.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">The current voluntary approach does not appear to be generating sufficient interest to encourage developers to opt for offsetting, or for providers to work up and get offsets accredited.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:12.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Strengthened national planning guidance, properly reflected in local planning policy, rather than new legislation may provide the market stimulus required to ensure that there is sufficient demand for offsets from developers.  The minerals sector is well placed to be an offset provider addressing the supply-side of the market.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction to the Mineral Products Association</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:12.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">The Mineral Products Association (MPA) is the trade association for the aggregates, asphalt, cement, concrete, dimension stone, lime, mortar and silica sand industries. With the recent addition of The British Precast Concrete Federation (BPCF) and the British Association of Reinforcement (BAR), it has a growing membership of 465 companies and is the sectoral voice for mineral products. MPA membership is made up of the vast majority of independent SME companies throughout the UK, as well as the 9 major international and global companies. It covers 100% of GB cement production, 90% of aggregates production, 95% of asphalt and ready-mixed concrete production and 70% of precast concrete production. Each year the industry supplies £9 billion of materials and services to the £120 billion construction </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">and other sectors. Industry production represents the largest materials flow in the UK economy and is also one of the largest manufacturing sectors.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The mineral industry’s track record</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:12.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">The minerals industry has an enviable and unrivalled track record of delivering net gain in biodiversity through innovative and imaginative site management and restoration.  A recent survey of a selection of our members identified that to date it has delivered over 5,000 hectares of priority habitat creation on its sites to date, with a further 5,000 hectares yet to be delivered but in approved restoration plans</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">.  In addition, we have recently started to map and publicise those restored sites with public access and wildlife interest in what we are calling our ‘National Nature Park’</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:12.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">The opportunity to do even more is recognised in research by the RSPB that identifies that that mineral sites could meet 100% of the targets for nine out of 11 priority habitats previously identified in the previous UK Biodiversity Action Plan</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">The quarrying industry's biodiversity contribution, a unique differentiator and defining characteristic of the sector, was praised by DEFRA Minister, Lord de Mauley, at the MPAs Restoration and Biodiversity Awards event at which he said: “These awards demonstrate the close relationship MPA and its members have built with wildlife organisations to enhance and protect biodiversity and will deliver a lasting legacy for wildlife.”  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">In addition Natural England’s Executive Director Paul Lambert also praised the industry saying that “The MPA’s commitment to restoring biodiversity and engaging with local communities is a shining example of what industry can do for people and for wildlife.  The MPA and its members are uniquely placed to deliver for nature through their management and restoration of sites. The Association is also uniquely placed to share their innovation and commitment with industry more widely. We look forward to continuing our partnership with the MPA to help business to recognise the value of the natural environment.”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">This potential is also recognised in the MPA’s Biodiversity Strategy</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">, first published in 2011, which makes  7 commitments to:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Extend our knowledge of biodiversity in and near to our sites</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Share best practice</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Develop partnerships for delivery</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Celebrate our successes</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Understand our contribution to national and local objectives</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Increase our influence, and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Promote education through our sites</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Biodiversity Offsetting</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">P</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">otential p</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ositives</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">The MPA is </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">supportive of the co</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">ncept of biodiversity offsetting.  We support the intention for offsetting </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">to help simplify and speed up the planning process, to make delivery of biodiversity enhancements more cost effective</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">, and reduce the bureaucratic and financial burden on industry.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">particular</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">, we </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">believe that there is a significant</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> opportunity for </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">our sector</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> to be</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> one of the main offset providers, reflecting its unique position as a major with a strong track record of delivering substantial biodiversity gains over the short and long terms particularly through management of its estate generally and more specifically through restoration of minerals sites to create habitats, often on a landscape-scale.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Of course, this will require demonstration that areas of habitat to be used or traded as offsets are additional to what would have been delivered anyway, generally through planning conditions or legal agreements.  This will require negotiation at the planning application stage, and flexibility by planning authorities, to recognise the scale of net gain that may be delivered from a site and to enable part of this to be considered as an offset.  In addition, long term management beyond the period of aftercare agreements could be funded through offsetting to ensure long-term value is maintained.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Potential negatives</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Minerals development differs from other types of development in that it can deliver long term net gains in biodiversity on or near site.  This is widely acknowledged and understood by the planning profession and conservation sector, and an offsetting system would need to recognise this to ensure that the sector is not required to deliver a disproportionate amount of offsetting before or as sites are worked.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">While we believe that offsetting should be delivered through the planning system, councils would need to be adequately resourced to do this.  We have serious </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">concerns </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">about</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> the ability of council planning departments</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">, particularly at district council level,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> to resource and manage the process</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> currently, evidenced by the time taken currently to produce sound plans and to process major planning applications, and our knowledge of cuts to planning departments and loss of ecological expertise.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> The pressure on local authorities is already huge and the system is failing to deliver plans at anything like the rate required for an effective ‘plan-led’ system.  Without biodiversity offsetting clearly embedded in plans, coupled with the right skills and capacity in place, converting aspirations into delivery will be difficult.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">We are aware that few offsetting projects appear to have emerged to date under the voluntary approach being trialled through the pilots</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">suggesting that the market has not developed as envisaged under a voluntary approach.  This may be due to a range of factors including:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.12pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Proper application of the mitigation hierarchy</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> with few </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">developments </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">resulting in significant residual biodiversity losses requiring compensation;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.12pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">the lack of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">sufficiently </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">clear and strong national</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> and local planning policy requiring</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> compensation for residual losses of non-designated habitats</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> leading to lack of demand for offsets</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.12pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">economic conditions and depressed construction sector during the period of the pilots leading to low demand for or willingness to pay for offsets;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.12pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">the onerous process of offset providers preparing and having schemes accredited</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> leading to lack of supply of offsets</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.12pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">lack of certainty that funding will be forthcoming to offset providers, and concern over the length of time an offset may need to be provided for ie what ‘in perpetuity’ may mean</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">, leading to lack of supply of offsets</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">It is unlikely that the mitigation hierarchy is ensuring that all affects are adequately mitigated.  Current planning policy and guidance is not as clear or strong as required to ensure that local planning policy and application of development management results in proper consideration of impacts on biodiversity, identification and quantification of residual effects, and requirement for compensation.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Strengthening national policy and guidance, and ensuring this is properly reflected in local planning policy and decisions would be the simplest means of introducing a system of offsetting.  Given sufficient demand for offsets from developments, the minerals sector is well placed be a major offset provider contributing to the supply-side of the market.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Minerals development should be acknowledged as being different to</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> other types of development as it is a temporary activity and results in net gain to biodiversity, particularly over the longer term.  This must be reflected in the application of offsetting to the industry.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The minerals sector should be acknowledged as having the potential to be a major offset provider</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">.  This will require flexibility on the part of planning authorities to allow some of the habitat created through site management or restoration to be used as an offset for other developments.  Long term funding from offsets could provide necessary long term funding for management of sites.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.99pt; padding-left:6.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">National planning policy and guidance should be strengthened</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> and properly reflected in local planning policy, to require offsetting of residual damage and thus stimulating the market for offsets.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">30 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> See for example MPA Press Release</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">No: 34/2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">17 October 2013  </span><a href="http://www.mineralproducts.org/documents/MPA_13-36-MPA_Restoration_and_Biodiversity%20_Awards_national.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.mineralproducts.org/documents/MPA_13-36-MPA_Restoration_and_Biodiversity%20_Awards_national.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><sp